{"key":"processedPost-13172910","value":{"id":13172910,"first":13170796,"last":13219191,"when":1284092566,"utime":"09/10/10 07:22 AM","cleanedPost":"<blockquote>Quote:<br /><strong>trippenballs said:</strong><br />I tip my dishes upside down after 3 days and seems to take care of any condensation still hanging around. I like to poor mine that hot it seems to give me very high low contam rate . The steam and heat kills contams let in when pouring</blockquote><br />Every time I see one of these threads, I hold my breath hoping someone won't repeat that bad info.&nbsp; Don't turn petri dishes upside down.&nbsp; The moisture will collect on the lid, and then flood the mycelium when you turn it right side up.&nbsp; In addition, moisture will fall out of the agar by gravity, compounding the problem.&nbsp; <br />The solution is to wait to pour until the agar has cooled off enough to pour without heat protection for your latex gloved hands.&nbsp; Pouring the agar hot does not kill contams let in while pouring.&nbsp; If anything, the excess heat draws in contamination as the agar cools.&nbsp; The solution is proper sterile procedure.<br />RR"}}